default2.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultVariations between minimum and “gold” standards amongst offshore helicopter operators are a source of concern in the specific area
defaults
default of pilot training
default and operating procedures
default. Bond and CHC, for example, only train their pilots to the
default minimum standard and industry sources tell RMT that this is because the companies are under no statutory obligation to achieve higher standards in this and other
default areas, so this extra cost is avoided. In our view, Norwegian standards should be adopted acro
defaultss the industry and this standardisation should be set in law.
default&#xa0;
default2.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHistorically, helicopter transport in the Norwegian sector of the North Sea was not as safe as that provided for their offshore colleagues in the UK. Between 1966 and 1989 the fatality rate wa
defaults 4.1 for the Norwegian sector and 3.7 for the UK sector per million person flight hours. This difference continued over the 1990s with a fatality rate of
default 
default1.6 in the UK compared to 2.3 in the Norwegian sector between 1990 and 1998. 
default&#xa0;
default2.7
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn the decade between 
default1999 and 2009, however, there were no fatal accidents in the Norwegian sector (a nil rate) whilst the UK’s fatality rate shot up to 5.6 – a deeply worrying reversal of the historic, downward trend across the North Sea. Furthermore, 11 out of the 12 helicop
defaultter accidents in the North Sea between 2001 and 2009 were in the UK sector.
default&#xa0;
default2.8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Norwegian sector has a different inspection regime and different regulations applying to helicopters and helicopter flights in the North Sea. All of these have been introduced over the last 12 years or so and explain the marked improvement in the safet
defaulty record. 
