default&#xa0;default3.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe role and effectiveness of the Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) 
defaultis at risk 
defaultfrom two recent developments. Firstly, we believe that proposals
default to extend the regulatory remit of the 
defaultE
defaulturopean 
defaultA
defaultviation 
defaultS
defaultafety 
defaultA
defaultgency (EASA)
default 
defaultto cover helicopter operations in the UK continental shelf will dangerously undermine the responsiveness and loca
defaultl knowledge of the UK offshore sector that the CAA has built up over a number of years
default. 
defaultRMT argue that member states with extensive helicopter operations central to the transport of workers in an industry should retain the powers to regulate that sector. 
default&#xa0;default3.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSecondly, the Coalition Government’s decision to
default 
defaultcut
default 120 posts 
defaultat the CAA is a serious threat to effective enforcement of the regulatory framework and, therefore, increases the risk to offshore workers obliged to use helicopter transport because transport
default by sea takes too long. 
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis is not to say, however, that there are no complaints about or concerns over the CAA’s regulatory performance. For example, the CAA’s response to the fatal incident off the coast of Shetland on 23
defaultrd
default August was not widely regar
defaultded as sufficiently strong to prevent a further decline in confidence of offshore workers in this mode of transport or the Super Puma models.
default&#xa0;
default3.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is also worrying that the CAA 
defaulthave only limited powers of enforcement on 
defaulthelicopters
default operating within the UK, 
defaultbut registered elsewhere.
default Clarity needs to be established in this area and we would prefer those regulatory standards to be brought up to a high level, rather than down to a lower level which is a potential consequence of EASA’s regulatory power grab.
default&#xa0;
default3.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn 
defaultour view, the Government should take its cue from the H
defaultelicopter Safety Steering Group (HSSG)
default on which the offshore trade unions, Health and Safety Executive, 
defaultCAA, 
defaultoil and gas industry representatives and helicopter operators sit, before taking any decisio
defaultns that affect the regulations applying to helicopter operators in the offshore sector.
default&#xa0;
default3.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFurthermore, in order to regain the confidence of the offshore workforce in helicopter transport, any decisions that the Government makes on the future regulatory fram
defaultework applied to offshore helicopter operations should be consulted on with workers and their trade union representatives,
default at the very least.
