default4.3 
defaultThe EC225 model was taken out of service following two non-fatal emergency ditchings in the North Sea in May and October 2012. 
defaultIt had only been returned to service in the offshore sector a matter of weeks before the fatal accident on 23
defaultrd
default August 2013 involving a Super Puma AS332 L2.
default&#xa0;
default4.4 
defaultTwo events prior to the 23
defaultrd
default August incident are 
defaultvital to consider in the context of offshore
default 
defaultworkers’ 
defaultconfidence in the safety of helicopter transport in the North Sea. Firstly, a survey of 1,600 offshore workers in May 2013 by the Step Change in Safety body, a coalition of the safety regulator HSE, the 5 trade unions and the oil and gas industry,
default found that nearly 9 in 10 (86%) of offshore workers did not trust the EC225 model. It was clear from this that trust in helicopter transport in general had declined significantly amongst the offshore workforce, before the fatal accident on 23
defaultrd
default August. As
default the Step Change in Safety official Les Linklater commented in industry press coverage of the May survey’s finding: “
defaultWe cannot think of this as an EC225 issue...The EC225 will come back and will be safe to fly again, but there are other airframes out there
default and there are confidence issues.”
default&#xa0;
default4.5 
defaultSecondly, the reported comments
default of a helicopter company (CHC) employee in response to an offshore worker’s concern over the safety of the EC225s has served to anger offshore workers and highlight a culture of macho bullying that exists with the tacit acceptance of the employers. Again t
defaulthis episode occurred before the accident on 23
defaultrd
default August, but also serves to highlight the problems over confidence in helicopter transportation that are ingrained in the workforce in the offshore sector.
default&#xa0;
default4.6 
defaultIt should also be noted that the “Boots On” cam
defaultpaign to reassure and support offshore workers was agreed and launched by
default members of
default the HSSG, in response to the 
defaultfurther concern over 
defaulthelicopter safety raised by the fatal incident on 23
defaultrd
default August. RMT believe that this unified approach is the most effecti
defaultve way of improving the health and safety of all offshore workers, on installations and on the helicopters used to transfer them to and from the workplace.
